Hi, folks,

here's the last COTD from the basic set:


    @{b}HONOR CHALLENGE@{ub}

    Interrupt, rare.

Plays just after an Away Team battle is initiated. Each Klingon with
Honor immediately kills one opponent with Treachery. Battle continues.

@{i}"The call to glory inspires the Klingon warrior to maximum fierceness and
honor, as symbolized by the Bat'telth champoinship trophy."@{ui}


One of the few battle-affecting cards from the base game, but one with a
good effect, especially if speed is a concern. Try it in any flavor of
Klingon Armada deck, where it works just great against Romulans and even
has some effect against the other affiliations (lots of the non-aligneds
have Treachery, too.) Its most important net effect is that you get to
tip the scales towards your side. If you have four honorable Klingons,
you can probably take on a Romulan away team of six or seven and still
expect to win the battle.

But its use goes a little farther and this is now also a viable
Federation strategy (though as a Fed you will first need to somehow get a
@{"Wartime Conditions" link "STCCG:cotd300.guide/CODT217"} out): Take a single expendable Klingon (perhaps the
key guy for the mission you just completed) and send him in alone to do
battle. He will of course lose, but not without taking an opponent's key
crewmember with him. Try this on an opponent who relies on @{"Devinoni Ral" link COTD142}
for Empathy or who tries a Mickey D. approach to a few quick points. Also
works great on these really annoying @{"Selas" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD23"} and @{"Taibaks" link COTD85} your Rommie friend
uses to complete his mission(s).

And for a maximum surprise effect (this is a late-game combo), play the
Klingon (and @{"Worf" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD35"}, K'Eleyhr and Alexander are equally good choices for
it) from your hand using a @{"Devidian door" link COTD146} once you're really ahead on
points and just need to stop your opponent from catching up before you
draw your last card. Fire the Klingon, stop the away team, eliminate a
key personnel and (hopefully) win the game! Just make sure you get him
there one turn before your opponent beams down, otherwise you'll not be
able to initiate battle. Also a good ploy for Feds: Deploy an Alexander
at some planet where your opponent is likely to attempt a mission. Wait
for beamdown, she'll hopefully attack you, you eliminate a key player and
have a great excuse to play a @{"Wartime Conditions" link "STCCG:cotd300.guide/COTD217"}. This will teach warlike
opponents to stay peaceful...


