@Node COTD152 "STCCG.guide/ST:CCG Card of the Day/Rishon Uxbridge"

        @{u}@{b}@{fg highlight}ST:CCG Card of the day@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}

        @{b}Wesley's STCCG card of the day #152@{ub}

Hi, folks,

here's a card of which some people think it's great, others think it's
crap:


    @{b}RISHON UXBRIDGE@{ub}

    Event, common AU.

Plays atop any one event card in play. Protects the underlying event from
@{"Kevin Uxbridge" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD20"}. However, @{"Kevin Uxbridge" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD20"} may remove (discard) Rishon. (not
cumulative). AU Icon.

@{i}"In his grief, the Douwd @{"Kevin Uxbridge" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD20"} re-created his dead wife, Rishon.
As if she were real, he responded to her tendency to keep him calm at
tense moments."@{ui}


Let's analyze who is right:

1) The "crap" argument: Hey, why should I play this card instead of just
another copy of the base event which would even help me get it out faster?
This argument is actually valid and in many cases will hold well.
However, there are a few exceptions, and that gets me to the other side:

2) The "not-so-crappy" arguments: First, there are a few vital cards
(@{"Red Alert" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD6"}) for which the above-mentioned argument does not hold, as you can't
use two of them in a deck when playing by tournament rules.

Second, you might want to use a Rishon to protect a key event on the
spaceline before nuking all others with a @{"Kev Ux: Convergence" link COTD191}.

Third, this also is a psychological card. Play @{"Red Alert" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD6"} - get it
@{"Uxbridged" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD20"}, play another @{"Red Alert" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD6"} - opponent will likely @{"Uxbridge" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD20"} it
again. However she might think twice before using up two @{"Kevins" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD20"} on the
same one @{"Red Alert" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD6"} card.

3) The "forget that - it's still crappy" arguments: Playing a Rishon
costs you a turn and turns are limited resources. This might just prove
too much work just for a single event, especially as most of them can do
their work quite quickly (@{"Red Alert" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD6"} is futile as soon as you have played
all your cards from your hand - you'll need to hoard cards to really use
it again, so why should I protect it instead of just using it ?)

And another one: Mind that @{"Kevin" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD20"} is an INTERRUPT! When your opponent
tries to play a Rishon, interrupt that play and nuke the underlying event
before Rishon hits the table! Result: Event discarded, Rishon will have
to find another target (and will be in for a rules hassle if there are no
more events to choose from...)

Also, why don't you just replace the Rishon with a Q2 giving you the
additional advantage of nuking that @{"Kevin" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD20"} instead of just avoiding him.

Net result: The crap side wins :-(


Favorite combo(s):

- @{"Anti-Time-Anomaly" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD21"} + Rishon (+ Temporal Rift): Your opponent might hold
  one @{"Kevin" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD20"}, but will she have TWO ?


