@Node COTD168 "STCCG.guide/ST:CCG Card of the Day/Revolving Door"

        @{u}@{b}@{fg highlight}ST:CCG Card of the day@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}

        @{b}Wesley's STCCG card of the day #168@{ub}

Hi, folks,

Another counterspell ?


    @{b}REVOLVING DOOR@{ub}

    Event, rare AU.

Plays on any Doorway card or @{"Iconian Gateway" link COTD180}. It is now closed. OR
Nullifies another Revolving Door (discard both) and "re-opens" card
underneath.

@{i}"A surreal door created by an unknown alien intelligence, found by the
@{"U.S.S. Enterprise" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD3"} on Theta 116 VIII. Open to entry but seemingly closed
to exit."@{ui}


This card is powerful. Very powerful. If you get it in your opening hand
you can cripple any deck that relies on any expansion cards (and which
deck worth that name does not ?). Note that I say any expansion cards,
as the future expansions will include a lot more Doorways and it will
get even worse...

The things you can get from this card are:

1) Slow your opponent's development. Always desirable.
2) Suck a @{"Kevin Uxbridge" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD20"}. Always desirable.
3) Kill her Revolving Door she planned to play or already played on your
   AU door in order not to lose your own speed. Always desir... I'm
   getting repetitive.

The risk behind it ? You might encounter an opponent who plays no AU and
no other expansion cards. One lost card. Great deal. Use the remaining 59.
Or you could only get it late in the game. Okay, you should have won by other
means at that point (The 500+ KBytes of COTDs just have to be good for
something:-) )

I'd use it in every deck from the start. You can always sideboard it out
after you've seen what you're up against, but I'd never miss the chance
to beat her horribly on the first game and start the second one with a
comforting lead.

Just don't think of including three of them in your deck to increase your
chances of playing it early. Too many is sometimes worse than too few.
And while you can normally afford to lose one card, losing three is
an entirely different business.

I might also bring back the point of usefulness in several play environments.
Consider (1) High-level play. Carefully tuned decks using every resource
available. You'll need one here - too many good AU cards nobody will pass
up. (2) Low-level play. Decks thrown together of the few cards you possess.
Probably also a decent AU ratio as they can't afford to leave out their
AU and still have a playable deck. If you have one here - use it!
(3) Mid-level play. Different story here. Enough cards to make a decent deck,
but not enough AU to really include a serious AU percentage. Three cards
maybe, just for coolness, but not enough that the Revolving Door will do
massive damage.


Favorite combo(s):

- Counterspells and combos just don't mix.


