        @{u}@{b}@{fg highlight}ST:CCG Card of the day@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}

        @{b}Wesley's STCCG card of the day #175@{ub}

Hi, folks,

seems I have to create another special edition... And no idea at all for
a Dream Card. So let's return to the basic variant and do two cards in
one article:


    @{b}AJUR & BORATUS@{ub}

    Personnel, Non-aligned, uncommon AU.

    Integrity 1
    Cunning 8 (Ajur) / 5 (Boratus)
    Strength 3 (Ajur) / 7 (Boratus)

    SECURITY, Once per game, if alone with Archaeology on a planet, may
    destroy all but 3 seed cards there (random selection). AU Icon. Staff
    star (Ajur only)

@{i}"A female Vorgon criminal from the 27th century who ruthlessly sought
artifacts with partner Boratus. Hunted the @{"Tox Uthat" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD11"} by returning to
2366."@{ui} (Ajur)
@{i}"Male Vorgon criminal from the future. Aims to steal artifacts with
partner Ajur. Once hunted the @{"Tox Uthat" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD11"} discovered by @{"Jean-Luc Picard" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD1"} on
Risa"@{ui} (Boratus)


Two really bad guys. And Integrity 1 only. (Firestorm!) But their special
ability is interesting. Destroying a lot of seed cards can help you or
hurt your opponent. If you ever get to destroy a lot. To make this
ability work, you need a location with at least four seed cards. And this
is not too probable, taking into consideration that you deduct 6
missions, 1 outpost and 1 AU door from your seed deck of maximum 30, so
the average number of seed cards per location is always below 4.

So they really only work against a deck that piles huge lots of Dilemmas
under one location. And in this case they work somewhat like a
@{"Senior Staff meeting" link COTD173}, destroying a few Dilemmas, with the risk to also remove
your crucial artifact. Hmm. Two cards instead of one, all the risks
involved, and just getting rid of a few measly dilemmas ? Nah, Better put
a few good personnel in my deck and overcome the Dilemmas in the regular
way. (Although there is one handy thing about them: Most players have no
way of keeping track of card order under the mission when randomly
selecting, so it might upset a carefully planned combination just by
reordering - imagine what it would do to my @{"Mirror Universe" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD100"}
combo...)

'Nother idea ? Yep. Better ? No. Play Ajur and Boratus and Vorgon
Raiders. Argh. A rare interrupt that needs two more rares to be playable
is not my idea of a good CCG card. And the fact that they all three are
destroyed makes it even worse. And all for one artifact. Nah. Better go
and recover one of mine from under a mission and get the points.

There actually IS a good use for the two, but that's part of a
soon-to-appear DOTW article (Hope I did not say too much here), so I'll leave
it as is and update the webpage with a revised edition some time next
week.


