        @{u}@{b}@{fg highlight}ST:CCG Card of the day@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}

        @{b}Wesley's STCCG card of the day #178@{ub}

Hi, folks,

those of you still reading rec.games.trading-cards.misc: Be warned, I
will no longer be on that group beginning from @{"#180" link COTD180}. Please you all move
over to the rec.games.trading-cards.startrek group where we now have our
new home.

Today it's time for a BIG nasty:


    @{b}KLIM DOKACHIM@{ub}

    Event, uncommon AU.

Plays on table. When opponent reports a unique personnel for duty,
opponent draws no cards at end of that turn.

@{i}"Zakdorn quartermaster controlling the Starfleet surplus depot at
Qualor II. A typical bureaucrat of the type that delights in delays that make
life difficult for officers"@{ui}


Bureaucrat ? Hmm. Sounds I invented this some time before (See the Dream
Card article on @{"Court-Martial" link COTD103}), and of course we play this with the house
rule "Unless Bureaucracy present, opponent draws..." and our Dream
Card personnel.

But back to the real game. This card is awful. Unless you happen to have
it on your side. Even the poorest kid has some unique uncommons and every
time one of them is played, you lose a card draw, effectively halving
your throughput in cards. And you cannot even circumvent it with some
extra draw effects like the @{"Traveler" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD4"}. Only a @{"Kivas" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD49"} works here. And that
one costs you your card play for that turn. Dang.

At least there is one card that partially neutralizes it: @{"Red Alert!" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD6"}
If you have an @{"Alert" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD6"} on the table, you can at least dispose of a lot of
uniques at the same time. And lose only one card draw with it. Which
gets me to the best killer combo since Gaps in Normal Space +
@{"Subspace Warp Rift" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD83"}: Klim Dokachim + @{"Yellow Alert" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD53"}! Play these two, and your
opponent will need at least TWO @{"Uxbridges" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD20"} to get back to any kind of
speed unless he plays a deck with nearly all universal crew. And while
he's getting those two @{"Kevins" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD20"}, you score some points. Like 100. Or so.
Of course that means nuking your own @{"Red Alert" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD6"}, so you'd better have some
decent crew on the table before you play the @{"Yellow Alert" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD53"}. Or you just
@{"Uxbridge" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD20"} your opponent's @{"Red Alert" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD6"} before playing Klim and he'll be
busy getting it back out of his discard pile. (Remember- only one
@{"Red Alert" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD6"} per deck under tourney rules!).

IMHO this card became way too strong. Like @{"Red Alert" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD6"} itself. It becomes
more and more a match on who draws which cards first. If I get my @{"Alert" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD6"}
out before you get your Klim and you can't nuke it, I am safe.
Other wise I'm in trouble. We will see yet more @{"Kevins" link "STCCG:cotd100.guide/COTD20"} now. Almost a little
boring. Like Channel in Magic.


